cpi: The Consumer Price Index is the indicator of consumer goods prices. This includes day to day aspects such as groceries, restaurants, transportation and cost of utilities, excluding accommodation expenses. A high CPI is good for the economy, but consumers are hit with high living costs. </br> </br> Western Europe has a very high CPI.
rent_index: An index of prices of renting apartments in the city. This value is relative to New York City. So low green values show cities where the rent is generally a lot lower than New York. Red values are on par, or more. </br> </br> In India, the rent price is generally less that 8% of New Yorkâ€™s.
cpi_plus_rent: This is an estimation of consumer goods prices including rent expenses. It outlines how accommodation costs can influence a city's overall affordability. These values are in relation to New York. </br> </br>  Cities in Switzerland and Norway make up most of the very few cities on par with New Yorks CPI+rent value.
groceries_index: An index of 'typical' grocery prices in the city. This includes fruit, vegetables, rice, milk, bread, meats and such. These values are relative to New York City. So low green values indicate the price of food is much less than it is in New York.</br> </br> South America is very low compared to the USA.
restaurant_index: A comparison of prices of meals and drinks in restaurants and bars in the city. These values are relative to New York. Red values show the city it is more expensive to go out to eat in, and green values show it is much less. </br> </br> Western Europe is generally very expensive to go out to eat or drink.
local_purchasing_power_index: This shows the relative purchasing power in buying goods and services in a given city for the average income. These values are relative to New York City. A high purchasing power means that an average wage can go a long way, a low purchasing power indicates that the average wage is not on a level with average costs. </br> </br> The USA leads the way here.
